This way we can capture the entire state of the error to determine.

Also worth doing: Including the entire error response in the returned object. This way, in cases like the 503 error in #2093 where the JSON payload isn't what our code expects. Things still work fine.

In that case, the 503 payload is

``` json
{
  "error": {
    "code": 503,
    "message": "Write collision, please retry.",
    "status": "UNAVAILABLE",
    "details": [
      {
        "@type": "type.googleapis.com/google.rpc.RetryInfo",
        "retryDelay": "1.000s"
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

This seems to be a JSON version of the [`google.rpc.status.Status`](https://github.com/googleapis/googleapis/blob/f03e356cd724ccda5056cfd6c54b78614ec4e6cc/google/rpc/status.proto#L78-L90) protobuf message type, with an extra `status` field that looks like a [`google.rpc.code.Code`](https://github.com/googleapis/googleapis/blob/f03e356cd724ccda5056cfd6c54b78614ec4e6cc/google/rpc/code.proto#L35).

Our error-payload-parsing code [makes the assumption](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/google-cloud-python/blob/af4f346e238e1a45ff5754335b9f8a4d98708e49/core/google/cloud/exceptions.py#L216-L217) that the errors come in the form:

``` json
{
  "error": {
    "message": "...",
    "errors": [
        "..."
    ]
  },
  "...": "..."
}
```

